04225nam a22005295i 9780300146233DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181996ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001462337 a10.12987/97803001462332doi  a(DE-B1597)486697  a(OCoLC)861792659  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a300/.1222/eng1 aHeimann, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFinding Philosophy in Social Science /cMary Heimann. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Why Philosophy? -- tPart A. From Fact to Theory -- t1. Fact -- t2. Idea -- t3. Inquiry -- t4. Systematization -- tPart B. From Explanation to Justification -- t5. Explanation and Prediction -- t6. Empirical Operations -- t7. Science et al. -- t8. Values and Morals -- tPart C. General Philosophical Problems in Social Science -- t9. Individualism and Holism -- t10. Systemism -- t11. Idealism and Materialism -- t12. Intuitionism, Empiricism, Pragmatism, and Rationalism -- t13. Subjectivism and Realism -- t14. Between Reason and Fact: Rational Choice Theory -- tAppendixes -- tReferences -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritten by an eminent and original thinker in the philosophy of science, this book takes a fresh, unorthodox look at the key philosophical concepts and assumptions of the social sciences. Mario Bunge contends that social scientists (anthropologists, sociologists, political scientists, economists, and historians) ought not to leave philosophy to philosophers who have little expertise in or knowledge of the social sciences. Bunge urges social scientists to engage in serious philosophizing and philosophers to participate in social research. The two fields are interrelated, he says, and important advances in each can supply tools for solving problems in the other.Bunge analyzes such concepts as fact, cause, and value that the fields of philosophy and social science share. He discusses assumptions and misassumptions involved in such current approaches as idealism, materialism, and subjectivism, and finds that none of the best-known philosophies helps to advance or even understand social science. In a highly critical appraisal of rational choice theories, Bunge insists that these models provide no solid substantive theory of society, nor do they help guide rational action. He offers ten criteria by which to evaluate philosophies of social science and proposes novel solutions to social science's methodological and philosophical problems. He argues forcefully that a particular union of rationalism, realism, and systemism is the logical and viable philosophical stance for social science practitioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030006606740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014623340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300146233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300146233/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY